Introduction

This is my course diary for the University of Helsinki course Data Visualization in R for PhD students. I’ll use this diary to record (mainly for myself) my progress on the course by including relevant exercises and assessments. Additionally I hope to use this diary to facilitate my own reflections and thoughts about data visualization more generally.

Below are my previous experience and expectations for the course. This was part of home assignment on the first lecture.

Previous experience

Courses on:

  • Basics of programming (Java)
  • Scientific computing (Python, Matlab and C)
  • Introduction to Open Data Science (R)
  • Machine learning (Python)

Additionally, I have done two simple online tools with Javascript that are used in research and in teaching. Actually, my lesson observation tool includes simple timeline visualization of observations that is drawn on HTML-canvas using only Javascript. It was rather interesting to figure out how to draw axes, ticks, labels and the data with just canvas methods.

I have mainly used Python in my analyzes and data visualization (Master’s thesis, two articles and few posters etc.). I plan to use R more in the future.

Expectations

I think I have quite good basic understanding of data visualization, but through this course I hope to refine and expand my knowledge and skills. I want to practice and become more proficient with R and ggplot2 as those have some benefits over Python. Additionally, there are some nice network analysis packages for R that I might need to use in the future.

Week 1

The first week had only three very basic exercises with base R and I completed with one simple r-script file. Thus, the first week exercises are not included in this course diary. However, I did set up github repository and this course diary webpage. Additionally, I loaned the course book Data Visualization: A Practical Introduction by Kieran Healy and The functional art: : An introduction to information graphics and visualization by Alberto Cairo. At a glance both seem interesting and useful.

Reflection

Unfortunately I missed first week lecture and exercise session as I was unaware I was accepted to the course. Foolishly I thought i would get notification via email, but Sisu is not smart enough system for that. I did go through the lecture slides and seemed that the content was interesting and engaging so I’m really disappointed I did not get to hear the lecture. Luckily, the first exercises were quick and easy so missing the first exercise session is not too worrisome.

Overall, I have the feeling I will like this course and will learn something new.

What happens if you use geom_jitter() instead of geom_point()?

Jitter seems to give some random variation or noise. This is confirmed by ggplot documentation.

df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = score, color = education)) + geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_light()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Exercise 3

3.1

Calculate the mean, standard deviation (sd), and number of observations (n) of score by education and age group. Also calculate the standard error of the mean (by using sd and n). Save these into a new data frame (or tibble) named edu_age_stats.

edu_age_stats <- df %>% group_by(education, age_group) %>% summarise(mean_score=mean(score), sd_score=sd(score), n=n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'education'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
# Compute standard error of mean as sd/sqrt(n)
edu_age_stats$se_score = edu_age_stats$sd_score/sqrt(edu_age_stats$n)

3.2

Using edu_age_stats, plot a bar plot that has age group on the x-axis, mean score on the y-axis, and education levels in subplots (facets).

Use geom_errorbar() to add error bars that represent standard errors of the mean.

edu_age_stats %>% ggplot(aes(x = age_group, y = mean_score)) +
  facet_wrap("education", labeller = "label_both") +
  geom_col(fill = "#fcd116") + # Color of our faculty for fun
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean_score-se_score, ymax=mean_score+se_score), colour = "#002b7f") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 8)) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Mean score", expand = c(0, 0), limits = c(0, 20)) +
  scale_x_discrete(name = "Age Group")

Reorder the levels of region based on mean_score.

df <- df %>% group_by(region) %>% mutate(mean_score=mean(score)) %>% ungroup()
df$region <- fct_reorder(df$region, df$mean_score, min)

Exercise 5

Using the data you modified in exercise 4.2, plot mean scores (x-axis) by region (y-axis) as points. The regions should be ordered by mean score.

Use stat_summary() to add error bars that represent standard errors of the mean.

df %>% ggplot(aes(mean_score, region)) +
  geom_point() + # All mean scores of each region at the same coordinates, geom_jitter would reveal this
  stat_summary(aes(score), fun.data = mean_se, geom="errorbar") + # Errorbars from scores
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Mean Score", breaks=c(10:20)) +
  scale_y_discrete(name = "Region")

iris_long <- iris %>% gather(key = "var", value = measure, -Species)

2.2

In iris_long, separate var into two variables: part (Sepal/Petal values) and dim (Length/Width).

Then, spread the measurement values to new columns that get their names from dim. You must create row numbers by dim group before doing this.

You should now have 300 rows of variables Species, part, Length and Width (and row numbers). Assign the result into iris_wide.

iris_wide <- iris_long %>% separate(var, c("part", "dim")) %>% group_by(dim) %>% mutate(row_no = row_number()) %>% spread(dim, measure)

Working with your own data

In exercises 3-5, you’ll work with your own dataset. If you don’t have you own data, use the fss_learning.csv data (see description below).

In these exercises, you are required to provide an overview of your data, using the tools we have learned so far. Because all datasets are different, the format of the exercises is quite open. You will get points for being thorough and trying your best - even if you didn’t know how to write something in code, be explicit with what you were trying to achieve. When submitting the exercises, please return both an .Rmd and an .html file! The HTML file created by previewing a Notebook (with the suffix .nb.html) is fine, but make sure that the HTML contains all the code and output that is needed for getting an impression of the data. In other words, the document needs to be readable without having access to the full dataset.

the fss_learning data

fss_learning.csv contains data from a longitudinal skill learning experiment. There are observations at multiple levels: a total of 18 participants, each completing 8 sessions which consist of 5 runs (trials) of a game-like driving task (i.e. 8*5 = 40 trials per participant). You can read more about the design here.

In the data, there are trial-level measures related to performance (number of collisions, duration in seconds, distance travelled), as well as self-reports on a scale of 1-7 (variables fluency:comp3) collected after each trial or session.

Let’s make it bigger with circular layout and nicer colors.

plot(g,
     layout = layout.circle(g),
     vertex.size=15,
    vertex.color="#009bff", 
    vertex.label.cex=0.5,
    vertex.label.color="white",
    vertex.frame.color="black")

Let’s now calculate network measures and use those for nicer plots.

# degree_centrality
df <- base::as.data.frame(degree(g))
colnames(df) <- c("deg")
# eigen_centrality
df$eig <- eigen_centrality(g)$vector
# page_rank
df$pr <-  page_rank(g)$vector
# Katz_degree
# There's no function to calculate katz-centrality. Need to make my own, if I plan to use R for my analyses.
df <- df %>% mutate(deg = as.integer(deg))

Also ggpairs-plot for the measures. All correlate nicely, as they should!

df %>% ggpairs(lower = list(continuous = "smooth"))

Plot with Kamada & Kawai layout and node size from node degree.

plot(g,
     layout = layout.kamada.kawai(g),
     vertex.size=df$deg,
     vertex.color="#009bff", 
     vertex.label.cex=0.7,
     vertex.label.color="black",
     vertex.frame.color="black")

Star plot with the Dude rightfully in the center and using eigencentrality to set the order and size of the nodes. It would be nicer to be able to set the starting point for the circular layout so that Walter would on top. I did not find a simple or easy way to do this.
